<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 34 companion (Making the Gate Real for the Developer — folds keys 77, 78). The chapter is
    CONFIG-centric: what it teaches lives mostly in configuration — a JaCoCo coverage report wired to a
    PR coverage platform, that platform's PR diff-coverage (new-code) threshold and its bot-comment
    policy, the CI step that uploads the report and decorates the pull request, and a Danger process
    rule. Those files (ci/coverage-pr.yml, .codecov.yml) are illustrative configuration; they are NOT
    run by this build. What is runnable and unit-tested here is the load-bearing DECISION the chapter
    argues for: the diff-scoped, ratcheting coverage gate in org.acme.coverage.CoverageGate (gate new
    code, fail on an overall-coverage drop, leave legacy until touched) and the diff-scoped bot-comment
    policy in org.acme.coverage.PrCommentPolicy (comment only on changed lines, filter by severity).
    JaCoCo runs over that code in the build, so `mvn -Pquality verify` exercises both the coverage tool
    the chapter wires AND the gate logic the config enforces — the two cannot silently drift (Chapter 34
    diff-scoping; Chapter 27 local/CI parity).

    This is a child module of the companion-code reactor. It sets <parent>, carries no groupId or
    version literal of its own, and inherits the runtime pin and the JUnit/AssertJ pins from the
    aggregator. JaCoCo is declared here because the aggregator does not manage it; its version literal
    traces to SOURCE-PIN.md §3. The static analyzers run via the `quality` profile (Checkstyle +
    SpotBugs, Chapter 16), self-contained under this module's own config/ dir like the peer key-33 and
    key-23 modules.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>coverage-pr-automation-platforms</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 34 — Making the Gate Real for the Developer (coverage-pr-automation-platforms)</name>

  <properties>
    <!--
      The coverage tool version the aggregator does NOT manage, pinned here to its SOURCE-PIN.md §3
      row. JUnit (junit-bom) and AssertJ are inherited from the parent's dependencyManagement and carry
      no literal here.

      SOURCE-PIN.md §3 pins JaCoCo 0.8.16, but that artifact is NOT published — Maven Central's latest
      is 0.8.15 (org/jacoco/jacoco-maven-plugin/0.8.16/ returns 404; the local cache holds only a
      .lastUpdated 404 stub for 0.8.16 and a real jar for 0.8.15). This module builds against 0.8.15,
      the real latest, which covers the anchor JDK 21 (JaCoCo support since 0.8.11) and the forward JDK
      25 (since 0.8.14). The same deviation the peer key-23 module hit, recorded in
      09-flags/48_jacoco_pin_0816_unpublished.md for a deliberate re-pin.
    -->
    <jacoco.version>0.8.15</jacoco.version>
  </properties>

  <dependencies>
    <!-- JUnit Jupiter — the harness; version managed by the aggregator's junit-bom import. -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <!-- AssertJ — the gate-decision and policy assertions. Version managed by the aggregator. -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <build>
    <plugins>
      <!--
        JaCoCo coverage, in the DEFAULT build (SOURCE-PIN.md §3 row; deviation 0.8.15 per the property
        comment). This is the coverage report a PR platform consumes: prepare-agent binds the agent into
        the test JVM via argLine (a module that sets <argLine> directly in Surefire would clobber it and
        silently report 0% coverage, so this module sets none); report writes target/site/jacoco/jacoco.xml
        — the machine-readable report Codecov/Coveralls/Sonar upload — plus the HTML observability surface;
        check enforces a BRANCH floor so a green build means the tool actually ran. The PR-scoped (new-code)
        threshold and the ratchet are the PLATFORM's job (.codecov.yml) and the runnable gate's
        (org.acme.coverage.CoverageGate) — this in-build check is the whole-module floor, not the diff gate.
      -->
      <plugin>
        <groupId>org.jacoco</groupId>
        <artifactId>jacoco-maven-plugin</artifactId>
        <version>${jacoco.version}</version>
        <executions>
          <execution>
            <id>jacoco-prepare-agent</id>
            <goals>
              <goal>prepare-agent</goal>
            </goals>
          </execution>
          <!-- tag::jacoco-pr-report[] -->
          <execution>
            <id>jacoco-report</id>
            <phase>verify</phase>
            <goals>
              <goal>report</goal>                 <!-- writes jacoco.xml — the report a PR platform uploads -->
            </goals>
          </execution>
          <!-- end::jacoco-pr-report[] -->
          <execution>
            <id>jacoco-check</id>
            <phase>verify</phase>
            <goals>
              <goal>check</goal>
            </goals>
            <configuration>
              <!--
                The in-build floor reads BRANCH, not only LINE (a line counts covered when one
                instruction on it ran, hiding an untested branch). The element/counter/value enum
                values trace to JaCoCo check-mojo.html. This is the whole-module floor; the new-code
                gate and the ratchet are diff-scoped and live in the platform config and the runnable
                CoverageGate, not here (gating whole-repo absolutes would block every PR, Chapter 34).
              -->
              <rules>
                <rule>
                  <element>BUNDLE</element>
                  <limits>
                    <limit>
                      <counter>BRANCH</counter>
                      <value>COVEREDRATIO</value>
                      <minimum>0.90</minimum>
                    </limit>
                  </limits>
                </rule>
              </rules>
            </configuration>
          </execution>
        </executions>
      </plugin>
    </plugins>
  </build>

  <profiles>
    <!--
      Static-analysis rule gates from Chapter 16, opt-in via `-Pquality`. The same self-contained shape
      as the peer key-33 and key-23 modules: the maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled engine, so
      the pinned engine is overridden via a plugin-level dependency (the "two-pin" lesson). The profile
      reads the config under this module's own config/ dir. Checkstyle includes the test source directory
      (the tests are first-class code held to the house ruleset); SpotBugs runs over main bytecode only.
    -->
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
